name: Mass-energy equivalence
description:
This formula states that the equivalent $energy$ $(\var{E})$ can be calculated as the mass $(\var{m})$ multiplied by the speed of light $(\const{c})$ squared. Similarly, anything having energy exhibits a corresponding mass $(\var{m})$ given by its energy $(\var{E})$ divided by the speed of light squared $(\const{c}^{2})$.
Because the speed of light is a very large number in everyday units, the formula implies that even an everyday object at rest with a modest amount of mass has a very large amount of energy intrinsically.

name: Pythagorean theorem
description: Where $\var{c}$ represents the length of the hypotenuse and $\var{a}$ and $\var{b}$ the lengths of the triangle's other two sides. The theorem, whose history is the subject of much debate, is named for the Greek thinker Pythagoras, born around 570 BC.
